title: Intelligence Analyst
description: Senior SIGINT Counter Terrorism Analyst, U.S. Army, US AFRICOM, UKMAY 2008 – JAN 2012 Provided direct support to CIP/COP in support of US operation Odyssey Dawn, assisting in Target acquisition and development and threat warning during US Combat operations Served as SIGINT SME in Intelligence Fusion cell in US AFRICOM Provided input in to National and Theater collection management planning and operational documents Input local targets into national databases in facilitating the development of Intelligence Requirements Provided direct support to deployed Intelligence collection missions, directing efforts and providing crucial reach back and threat warning to deployed personnel Senior Analyst/TENCAP Operator, U.S. Army, Camp Humphreys, South Korea APR 2007 – APR 2008 Maintained TENCAP equipment providing vital information to all Intelligence operations for the Korean Peninsula Provided near real-time intelligence and daily situational and threat briefings to commanders and national-level consumers in tactical and strategic settings Performed ELINT and COMEXT analysis, providing Indications and Warnings in support of personnel in the field and ongoing missions SIGINT Mapping and Analysis Cell Analyst, U.S. Army, NSA, HIJUN 2002 – APR 2007 Performed basic traffic analysis in support of identification and activity awareness and product reporting Developed intelligence information on new target activities and technologies for customers including first, second, and third party customers Provided customers with a first look at new technologies and target use of those technologies using GEO Spatial metadata analysis tools Used extensive target knowledge and language ability to update national databases and ensure Intelligence Community access to vital target information Processed raw intelligence data into finished tactical and strategic reporting products in accordance with RFIs and standing Information needs

title: Technical SIGINT Analyst
description: •Provided personally tailored all-source intelligence and produced intelligence products to support Electronic Warfare (EW) customers and provide users with potential means of access to EW threat databases in NSA’s Electromagnetic Space Analysis Center. •Delivered all-source targetable and operationally actionable intelligence information relating to electromagnetic capabilities and potential means of access to those targets, using collaborative tools, knowledge, databases and detailed analysis •Served operational users’ needs, ensuring ready access by information operations planners, operators, and developers to all holding information that assists in the preparation of the electronic battle space and electronic mapping of targets. •Prepared relevant assessments on emerging threat issues as well as vulnerabilities and opportunities of key CI targets. •Gathered signals intelligence (SIGINT), human intelligence (HUMINT), counter-intelligence (CI) and utilized web-based research on classified and unclassified networks to analyze intelligence information. •Analyzed all-source intelligence to assist in the production, indications and warning, collection management, targeting, imagery and network analysis, related to counterintelligence (CI) and counter-terrorism (CT) operations. •Prepared relevant assessments on emerging threat issues as well as vulnerabilities and opportunities of key CI targets. •Research and analyze Counterintelligence Assessments and CI analytical products. •Provided training to personnel on the GALE-Lite 4.5 analysis tool which allows users the capability to perform operational even and all-source analysis, near real-time data fusion, situational awareness and operational planning in a single environment. •Tracked and analyzed targets of interest in the EUCOM and CENTCOM AOR tasked by NSA/CSS •Monitored databases and dissemination systems to provide time-critical threat analysis, target identification, and geo-location data.

title: ELINT Analyst
description: •Utilized all-source analysis to perform Indication and Warning (I&W) and provided expert electronic intelligence (ELINT) analysis, ship tracking, and implemented overhead collection coverage plans for tactical and strategic military. •Supervised four junior analysts, ensuring proper tracking and reporting of maritime vessels of interest. The “go-to” analyst on the National Maritime Intelligence Center Watch Floor. •Provided all-source analysis and reporting in response to requests for information (RFI’s) from the Intelligence Community regarding radar threat environments and radar capabilities. •Managed all day-to-day ELINT operations and coordinated training for junior personnel insuring operational requirement we met for the watch team. •Tracked over 1000 maritime vessels of interest, in support of Homeland Security, creating over 100 new files to enhance the common intelligence picture. •Utilized knowledge of foreign order of battles (OOB) to provide military leaders and analyst with information on tactics, training and strategies of landbased, shipborne, and airborne assets. •Provided fusion analysis of ELINT with COMINT, IRINT, IMINT, and PROFORMA which greatly enhanced tactical and strategic commander’s battle force picture and provided situational awareness to deployed units worldwide.

company: Overview of Smart Cities and the role of “Safe” in Smart Cities:
description: Some of the other factors that drive Safer City projects are: a strong city economy, level of safety and security threat, availability of internet protocol, susceptibility to natural disasters, improved private and public partnership, and so on. ‘Safer City’ concept is expected to witness significant traction over the next few years as external/internal threat factors are given more importance by governments across the world. The higher the internal/external threat of terrorist attacks, the more probability there is of a city implementing a safer city project. In terms of adoption, the North American market has already seen some rapid progress after the 9/11 attacks. New York City is one of the most “surveilled” cities in the world with video surveillance cameras located at almost every junction, intersection, building, and public area in the city. Other major cities such as Tokyo, Los Angeles, and so on, are on the forefront in adopting safer city projects and related technologies. As critical assets in a city’s infrastructure, security technologies and solutions in future cities will play an important role in promoting better well-being and will support city operators to better cope with security and safety challenges. In the next 5-10 years, Frost & Sullivan expects safer city projects to become integral part of a city’s development schemes proposed by the respective governmen

Assisted in troubleshooting issues and rapidly solving problems/correcting defects.

title: Digital Network Intelligence Analyst
description: - Provided SIGINT and DNI analytic support to both strategic and tactical missions—lead DNI analyst for both Operation Iraqi Freedom and Operation New Dawn. - Conducted digital network analysis of cyber activities to identify entities of interest, including their methods, motives, and capabilities. - Determined malicious behavior and recognized emergent patterns and linkages to visualize the larger picture of cyberbased operations. - Devised all-source analytic/collection strategies while applying knowledge of network fundamentals and open-source tools to pursue target access and exploitation. - Performed queries and analysis using national databases in support of counterterrorism missions, facilitating national level reports that led to the detainment of 14 High-Value Targets.

title: Tactical Ground Sigint Specialist
description: • Conducted operations position in support of the Regional Command South and International Security Assistance Forces-Afghanistan. • Conducted support to ground SIGINT collection operations, SIGINT operations coordination and synchronization, and other SIGINT activities. • Supports the timely, relevant, accurate and predictive SIGINT and Electronic Warfare support to enable the commander and subordinate unit commanders the ability to understand their battlespace and enemy forces. • Provided indications and warnings tipping and force protection reports. • Provided support to the Brigade Combat Teams. • Provided routine and recurring support to SIGINT activities. • Responsible for monitoring unevaluated traffic as it is received by the KIFC ONEROOF server resident on NSANet, and manipulates it as required to ensure proper processing. • Operated on ground geo-location systems, targeting packages, and tracked HVI’s • Used SIGINT databases and geo-tools to provide information on HVI’s • Performed SIGINT targeting through meta-data analysis and collection for geospatial reporting. • Utilize Google Earth, Pinwale, NKB, and other Geo-location aids in daily operations. • Produced near real time actionable intelligence during several active enemy engagements, to include passive Geo-location missions. • Provided detailed, time-sensitive reports and threat warnings that revealed enemy intentions and Locations

title: Sigint Analyst
description: Performed initial collection and analysis to establish target identification and communications pattern of forces in South America and Mexico.  Operated and trained on ground and airborne geo-location systems, targeting packages, and tracked HVI’s  Used SIGINT databases and geo-tools to provide information on HVI’s  Maintained analytical working aids to support target collection, identification and location of mission targets.  Performed fusion analysis of SIGINT products with support of Geospatial Intelligence and Cryptologic Linguist.  Write, edit, evaluate and publish SIGINT reports.  Prepare and present weekly summary briefings to site leadership regarding local Signals Intelligence collection  Experienced or trained on multiple airborne signal intelligence collection and location systems including Guardrail, GREENDART, Pennantrace, and AIR HANDLER.  Train newly arrived Linguists and Analysts on mission duties and standard format for reports.  Provide intelligence analysis and report writing in support of missions in South America and Mexico. Maintain continuity of mission files necessary to the overall operations of the mission.  Support Customs and Border Protection and the Department of Homeland Security counter-narcotics and counter-human trafficking operations by using Aerial Reconnaissance Exploitation System.  Instructed soldiers on how to focus mission collection, operation center procedures and to maintain unit readiness to deploy at any time.  Supported of NORTHCOM operations for Mexico in San Antonio, Texas. While there I worked to collaborate with the host nation and NSA Texas to provide near real time intelligence for force protection and long term pattern of life analysis. During my time I processed and passed over 500 reports with significant geo locations to the host nation and to NSA Texas to populate the national SIGINT database.

title: Senior Signals Intelligence Analyst
description: Responsible for researching reviewing and reporting SIGINT reports to identify and nominate targets of interest that may be potential terrorist threats to the U.S or its allies, according to specific watchlisting criteria directed by Homeland Security Directive Number 6. Perform research and analysis on targets meeting specific watchlisting criteria utilizing specific databases such as Anchory /Maui, Nymrod, Pathfinder, Octave, Skywriter, Semester, Pinwale, SIGINT Navigator, Association, CPE, and other automation tools in response to specific analyst request in order to produce clear, concise and accurate reports for inclusion in NCTC's Terrorist identities Datamart Environment (TIDE) database.

title: Supervisor/Signals Analyst
description: NSA Evaluate geographic imagery, monitor and collect signals, and analyze the data to issue tactical reports in support of mission objective. Responsible for information distributed to NSA senior leadership, DOD customers and Military Commanders in support of national security. Served 12 months as the Maritime Support Watch Officer, on a 24/7/365 watch floor, an Intelligence Community wide essential watch that provides intelligence and support to complete missions. Performed Conducted All-source analysis, I&W and database management for two high - interest targets ensuring 100% continuity. Supervise and mentor 15 Sailors - monitor daily activities, provide semi-annual counseling and deliver annual performance evaluations.

title: Electronic Watch Officer
description: Managed 500 soldiers in maintenance, programming , inventory and accountability of 43 electronic countermeasure systems valued at $6M leading to 98% full mission capability.Advised BN commanders on conduct of electronic warfare, remote-controlled IED threats, system interoperability, training,RF spectrum, joint spectrum interference resolution, system sustainment supporting 24/7/365 route clearance operations.Sole Crew instructor for Task Force Iron Claw Academy, an intense seven day course designed to give soldiers a better understanding of (ECM) electronic countermeasure environment in Iraq. Working with civilian counter-parts for Joint Improved Explosive Device Defeat Organization (JIEDDO).Trained 814 soldiers on crew systems. Qualified 325 operators in the deployment of crew systems; trained an additional 531 soldiers on theory and installation of the system directly increasing readiness and combat survivability of two battalions.

title: Senior SIGINT Analyst
description: for a fast-paced, in-demand, and highly sensitive work section within the CENTCOM Area of Responsibility Provide time-sensitive and critical intelligence to partner organizations as well as long-term strategic intelligence missions Acquired and reported about communication and electronic signals that are used to support the SIGINT and information assurance missions of the NSA Conducted research to achieve identification and better sources of intelligence, providing for better access to high-priority operations and continuity as telecommunication capabilities are enhanced Drafted and reviewed reports on high value targets; keeping customers aware of ever changing high-interest military reorganizations, order-of-battle, disposition of forces, and other technological advances Used Anchory/MAUI, Dishfire, OCTAVE, CINEPLEX, GLOBALREACH, ARCGIS, ASSOCIATION, SIGNAV, NSAnet, RT-RG Interface Tools, ANB, Renoir, Google Earth, and Microsoft Office Tools daily Used PINWALE, MARINA, Agility, and AIRGAP weekly Used UIS, Beamer, UTT, and CPE monthly; Conduct radio direction-finding operations to determine locations of threat emitters. Provided indications and warning data and threat warning information (force protection) to the locally supported tactical unit. Provided technical data to larger SIGINT enterprise. Performed operator-level preventive maintenance on SIGINT and communications equipment. Provide information for SIGINT reports to US government personnel for editing and release.

title: Insurgent Network / Identity Exploitation / Intelligence Analyst
description: • Experience working in a 24x7x365 Security Operations Center (SOC)& Sensitive Compartmented Information Facilities (SCIF) • Familiarity with Intelligence Organizations, Disciplines, Systems, Analysis, Security, Processes • Responsible for Exploiting, analyzing, researching, reporting, database management and dissemination C-IED/RCIED mission analysis briefings and annexes, High Value Individual targeting products, Mobile C4 Networks, THREAT NETWORK model analysis, Insurgent IED cell activities, Analyzing links and nodes, and All-Source exploitation of documents and media from C- IED operations and detainees. • Responsible for Intercept, Identify, Classify and determine the source and location of hostile Communications and Radio Signals • Knowledgeable in SIGINT, COMINT, ELINT, GEOINT, MASINT, IMINT, HUMINT, •Counterintelligence, All-Source Analyst, Counterterrorism, Physical Security •Familiarity with Army intelligence systems/platforms that the TCC interacts with: JCATS, CIDNE, DCGS, DCGS-A, JSTARS, IWS, TES, DTES, GRCS, PROPHET, etc. • SIGINT capabilities include the collection and exploitation of communication signals and interception of electromagnetic signals, such as radar and weapons systems, for Electronic Intelligence (EI). • Performed SIGINT/COMINT Target Development for analysis of sea, air, and ground platforms • Experienced with Guardrail Common Sensor (GRCS), Communication High Accuracy Airborne Location System (CHAALS), and Advanced QUICK LOOK (AQL) •Familiarity Find, Fix, Finish, Exploit, Analyze and Disseminate (F3EAD) battle command process. • Knowledge of Foreign Satellite Interception (FORNSAT), Radio Frequency (RF), and SCS systems capabilities •Provided support to the ISR (Intelligence, Surveillance, and Reconnaissance) synchronization process • Knowledge of Satellite communication (SATCOM) communications and systems • Knowledgeable of Defense & Space four Orbit regimes •Familiarity (F3EAD) battle command process.

title: Ground SIGINT Analyst and Reporter
description: • Conducted time sensitive reporting in a concise accurate manner for the Afghanistan Remote Operations Cryptologic Center (AROCC) in support of International Security Assistance Force (ISAF) operations and Collection Management Authority (CMA) requirements. • Performed evaluation, sanitization, and quality assurance measures of reports based on AROCC reporting branch SOP and NSA policies. • Personally have written or conducted quality control of a combined 23,000 + Klieglight formatted reports. • Responsible for recognizing and reporting advance threat warnings to protect Coalition Forces. • Maintained existing IJC reporting criteria guidelines and created new reporting standards to ensure tailored SIGINT products and relevant information was disseminated to the customer. • Coordinated with both on and off site SIGINT teams to ensure that our products populated the appropriate databases for widest possible dissemination. • Performed duties directly in support of foreign release (FORREL) requests for information (RFI). • Supervised the execution of routine reporting branch operations and accounted for shift personnel. • Responsible for the training, both initial and advanced, of multiple employees to a common standard while still conducting my regular duties. • Identifying, diagnosing, and troubleshooting communications and system issues; report unresolved issues to support personnel. • Maintained local archives of all final products, ensuring their orderly storage and adherence to naming conventions.

title: 35N Signals Intelligence Analyst (with Deployment to Afghanistan)
description: • Was considered the subject matter expert for T-LITE, TMRRS, and TSPRING systems. • Completed DEPL2000 training at NSA-G. • Served 6 months in the AIRHANDLER Shop at NSA-G conducting geolocation operations and time sensitive reporting for the theaters of Iraq and Afghanistan. • Created and maintained databases to provide in-depth analysis as well as Tacrep and Klieglight formatted reports to ensure that operators had quick and easy access to up to date information on multiple target groups. • Deployed to Afghanistan November 2009-March 2010 as Lead SIGINT Analyst establishing the Joint Interrogation and Detention Center (JIDC) SIGINT Cell and used Analyst Notebook, ANCHORY/MAUI, OCTAVE, RENOIR, TAPERLAY, SHARKFINN, RT-RG to conduct critical analysis. • Worked closely with Human Intelligence (HUMINT) personnel and various branches of service in a cooperative and cohesive environment in order to maximize intelligence efforts and produce the highest quality product. • Performed operator maintenance on surveillance systems, organic communications equipment, light wheeled vehicles and power sources. • Performed research using various resources, databases and tools in order to maintain awareness of mission target and facilitate the accomplishment of specific mission requirements. • Became familiar with UIS, GLAIVE, DRT, TMRRS, MOONSHINE and STILETTO • Conducted analysis and reporting on TMRRS, TSPRING, MOONSHINE and DRT using programs such as: UIS, GLAIVE, STILETTO and ALASKA • Learned how to effectively set up the TMRRS, TSPRING and DRT systems within 25 minutes • Quarterly conducted set up of a fully operating and working T-SCIF • Obtained a strong knowledge-base on GSM, VHF/UHF networks, and GMA

title: Senior Cyber SME/ All-source-SIGINT Analyst
description: - Liaised with partners to identify gaps in IO system capabilities, map existing/planned CNO capabilities against COCOM requirements, and align mission planning to the Integrated Joint Special Technical Operations review and approval process. - Directed the activities of personnel conducting analysis, planning, development, and cyber operational initiatives - Uses various tools to facilitate partner CNO tasking and QC partner’s CNO tasking requests. - Involved with NSA/TAO Cyber mission planning, coordination, and deconfliction process. - Provided SIGINT/CYBER information and threat warning, during real time global operations for multiple U.S. and partner organizations using support tools and real-time source databases. - Conducted operations for Fleet combatants and shore commands; supporting EUCOM, AFRICOM, CYBERCOM, and NSA/CSS. - Project manager for multiple missions in hostile locations, spanning equipment installs, trouble shooting, personnel training, budget management, diplomatic relations, collection and logistics - Collection manager in support of aerial operation to include combat operations and provided tasking for theater level commanders. Identified collection priorities daily, corrected data flow problems and provided weekly statistics on accuracy of data. - Primary cyber intelligence analyst for all operations, eliminating incorrect collection and providing a “First Look” on all collection to turn around actionable intelligence within 24 hours. - Liaison with foreign partner providing CNO/SIGINT training, tasking, budgeting, and overall diplomatic relations. - Assistant Cryptologic Resource Manager; planned, managed and tasked collection and intelligence assets in accordance with U.S. Navy and NSA/CSS priorities. QC’d all reports from U.S. Naval Vessels in the EUCOM/AFRICOM AOR. - Managed, administered, and maintained all Special Access Program personnel, equipment, and accesses without a single discrepancy for four years.

title: Intelligence Analyst
description: • Compile, collate, analyze, produce, and evaluate intelligence and provide subject matter expertise in direct support of U.S. PACOM requirements supporting a variety of tasks and disciplines • Write and produce intelligence summaries, estimates, targeting packets, and visual graphic presentations to convey the current common operating picture derived from multi-discipline intelligence sources • Conduct basic and advanced target development in response to Joint Chiefs planning order • Update integrated data base (MIDB) entries that enabled intelligence community target vetting • Conduct target vetting in coordination with two combatant commands and four national agencies • Support PACOM J3 operations planning team and Commander's estimate brief • Assist with long range planning and coordinate intelligence and targeting efforts within USPACOM, with STRATCOM Headquarters and with the Intelligence Community • Assist in the development, vetting and validation of target materials, and with the management of target lists • Produce required target materials that include, but are not limited to, Electronic Target Folders (ETFs), Target System Analysis (TSA), Battle Damage Assessments (BDA), and technical analysis reports • Utilize intelligence tools, including MIDB and interfaces such as Morpheus, Gemini, and the Joint Targeting Toolbox (JTT) • Utilize a wide-range of research and analytic tools and techniques in order to conduct target intelligence, operational research and analysis and to provide recommendations to the J2, J3

title: Signals Intelligence (SIGINT) Analyst
description: Security Clearance: TS//SCI w/CI POLY Perform detailed analysis to reveal target network communications nodes, structures, operating procedures, and mediums for additional exploitation. Recover, correlate, and fuse technical, geographical, and operational intelligence information. Recognize and exploit intelligence information. Author time-sensitive intelligence reports in accordance with established guidelines for U.S. warfighters and national decision makers. Produce, analyze, study, research, fuss, and correlates intelligence for strategic, operational, and tactical customers. Provides target geopolitical and operational intelligence to national agencies and military command authorities. Identify and disseminate real-time threat warning information. Develop and employ techniques to identify and exploit target network configurations and operating characteristics. Reconstruct target communication profiles through in-depth analysis of message address information and routing indicators. Create and maintain technical and operational databases using diverse computer hardware and software applications. Operate mission-essential communications mediums. Produce and present topical high-interest technical and operational intelligence briefings to all levels of command. Use all-source intelligence information. Prepare target communications assessments, adversary order of battle studies, situation reports, and other intelligence reports are required. Conduct Information Operations, provide analysis for Information Warfare activities and support to Air Operations Centers and supported commanders. Provide detailed support to the contingency and deliberate planning process.

title: Adjunct Professor
description: English 0955 – Developmental Reading and Writing English 0960 – Developmental Writing English 1010 – Introduction to Writing English 2010 – Intermediate Writing English 2020 – Writing for Scientists and Engineers Reporting 2111 – Mechanics of Report Writing Reporting 3222 – Advanced Report Writing Reporting 4398 – Releaser/Certifier Course Academic Committees: Beat Club, Assistant Faculty Advisor Writing Club, Assistant Faculty Advisor Academic Interests: Romantics Horror, Science Fiction, and Fantasy Literature Recent Publications/Presentations: "Lost at Sea," Morpheus Tales, #XVII, July 2012. "On Sale," 605 Magazine, Vol. 3, No. 3, March 2011. “Famille du Jour” and “Glüton’s Christmas Eve,” Fast Forward: A Collection of Flash Fiction, Volume 2, Fast Forward Press, 2009 “Mercy,” Fast Forward: A Collection of Flash Fiction, Volume 1, Fast Forward Press, 2008 “The Role of Fate in Macbeth and Literature,” Arts and Humanities Honors Presentation, Weber State University 31 October 2006 Excerpt from “Some Kind of Monster,” Guilty as Charged: 32nd Summer Writing Program Magazine, The Jack Kerouac School of Disembodied Poetics, Summer 2006 Fast Forward Press, editor, Boulder, Colorado, http://www.fastforwardpress.org/ Fear Knocks, the e-journal of horror and suspense, editor, http://fearknocks.com Philosophy of Teaching: I see my teaching role as that of a guide on a wonderful journey discovering the English language in writing and reading. I take my students beyond the tourist hot spots and into the hole-in-the-wall cafes, street markets, and sometimes unsafe neighborhoods, where they develop more than just grammar, spelling, punctuation, and required writing skills, but acquire a love of language.

title: Signals Intelligence Analyst
description: I conducted target analysis and technical research, as well as Signals Intelligence Analysis (SIGINT) for combatant commanders and national decision-makers. Participated in multiple missions as a Tactical Ground SIGINT Specialist. Prepared briefings and tactical and technical reports. Led and trained soldiers to help improve their proficiency in tactical and technical skills. Provided mentoring and guidance for junior soldiers. Supervised ten cleared personnel, ensuring all tasks assigned were completed in a timely manner. Managed and secured over $2 million worth of sensitive equipment without a loss.

title: Mid-Level Geolocation Analyst
description: Geo-locational Technical Analysts support strategic and tactical intelligence organizations in a dynamic technical operations center, developing, refining, and producing geo-locational data to support the development of various intelligence reports. Manage and facilitate the prosecution of collection-related data files, manipulate complex SIGINT receivers and signal processors, and produce reliable geo-locational data and intelligence information. Conduct general and directed searches, and perform target development efforts within a 24/7 operations. operate in a dynamic mission environment, able to multi-task across multiple technical efforts simultaneously, and communicate effectively through virtual and chat-based communications. Geo-location • Operational experience in geo-location in strategic or tactical organizations as an analyst. • Experience performing communications or signals intelligence collection. • Formal training in Passive Geo-locational techniques. • Experience with ground, airborne, and/or national geo-location systems. • Direction-finding (DF), and exploiting SIGINT internals to corroborate and expand locational data and target disposition. • SIGINT operations with ground, airborne and other platforms. • Knowledge of GSM theory, technology and networks. • Previous intelligence collection/target experience within the Middle East. • Direct Signals Intelligence (SIGINT) support to deployed military elements. • Identifying, evaluating and providing Indications and Warning (I&W), tipoffs, and other direct-support data and information to forward-deployed elements. • Conducting Pattern of Life analysis, developing target packages, or managing multiple collection mission priorities simultaneously in a live environment. Familiarity/experience with any of the following: METRICS,ELCC, SURREY, INTELINK, Google Earth, Tower Power, AIRHANDLER, ELCC, WITCHHUNT, Assured Pursuit, SIGINT Analysis Techniques.

title: Signals Intelligence Analyst/Product Reporter
description: • Issued SIGINT reports to national level consumers as a Signals Intelligence Analyst/Product Reporter • Conducted research, in-depth analysis, and writing of over 100 time-sensitive KLIEGLIGHTS, over 80 mission specific reports, and contributed to over 260 reports that received executive, senior, or presidential level feedback • Trained two new personnel that achieved a score of 100% on the Job Qualification Readiness (JQR) reporting evaluation (Training included daily use, memorization, and understanding of all current USSIDs and reporting programs specifically CPE and MESSIAH) • Provided real time direct threat warnings to support CENTCOM and PACOM missions • Program manager for a team of three multi-service individuals on shift for real time collection Direct Threat Warning (DTW) missions and multiple other mission requirements • Developed and maintained multiple target databases • Pioneered mission use and trained 95% of mission team on the use of GALE-Lite to improve analytical skills and mission effectiveness. • Daily prepared and delivered mission briefings to NSA Senior Leadership • Daily usage of Intelligence analyst tools, USSID’s, and databases including, but not limited to; ANALYST’S NOTEBOOK, PINWALE, CPE, MESSIAH, GALE-LITE, HOMEBASE, CADENCE, ArcGIS, ARCVIEW, SEDB, DISHFIRE, MAINWAY, TAPERLAY, RENOIR, OCTAVE, ANCHORY/MAUI, AIRGAP, AMHS, INTELINK, UIS, CONTRACTIVE, GEOFINDER, GOOGLE EARTH, and OILSTOCK, Microsoft Office 2007, Outlook, Word, Power Point, and Excel including experience with pivot tables

title: Technician II Network Operation Day Shift Lead
description: Managed a team of 14 to 17 technicians in day to day operations in the South NOC for T-Mobile. I motivated and lead the DDS team to complete network goals and assist in the individual growth of team members in the skill needed in the DDS role. I prioritized and escalated all issues internally and externally sourced. Verified circuit delivery on wireless voice and data networks thru multiple transmission mediums RFC tested and turned up cell sites while documenting all procedures to enhance and speed up the time required to turn up a cell site, while eliminating duplicated work orders and effort Used programs such as: Homer, Citrix, Granite, ALU SAM 5620, NetExpert, PuTTY manager, Insite, Microsoft Outlook, Excel, including experience with pivot tables, Word, Sliped, IPControl Daily Processing up to 1,400 work orders, trouble tickets as well as creating trouble tickets and tasks when needed for alarmed cell sites, or contacted switch operators and field technicians to troubleshoot the alarm Programmed, tested, troubleshoot, provisioned, pushed operating system firmware upgrades, verified configurations, checked alarm functions monitoring, and supported multiple devices including, ALU 7705 and 7750 routers, Cisco 7609 routers, JDSU Collector, MSO and site NID's, and JDSU QT600 test heads Utilized the CLI and/or the GUI to configure and test ALU 7705, 7750's and JDSU NID's Contacted vendors and equipment manufactures to create trouble tickets for repair of sites, equipment, VLAN's and cabling Troubleshoot problems with devices, connections, VLAN's, broadcast storms, vendors or other service or none-service impacting situations Trained NOC personnel in live site reprovisioning of cell site NIDs Assisted Field techs in restoring 2G & 3G service to cell sites Experienced in troubleshooting microwave, COW, and COLT cell sites for high priority events

title: Signals Intelligence Analyst/Product Reporter
description: • Issued SIGINT reports to national level consumers as a Signals Intelligence Analyst/Product Reporter • Conducted research, in-depth analysis, and writing of over 100 time-sensitive KLIEGLIGHTS, over 80 mission specific reports, and contributed to over 260 reports that received executive, senior, or presidential level feedback • Trained two new personnel that achieved a score of 100% on the Job Qualification Readiness (JQR) reporting evaluation (Training included daily use, memorization, and understanding of all current USSIDs and reporting programs specifically CPE and MESSIAH) • Provided real time direct threat warnings to support CENTCOM and PACOM missions • Program manager for a team of three multi-service individuals on shift for real time collection Direct Threat Warning (DTW) missions and multiple other mission requirements • Developed and maintained multiple target databases • Pioneered mission use and trained 95% of mission team on the use of GALE-Lite to improve analytical skills and mission effectiveness. • Daily prepared and delivered mission briefings to NSA Senior Leadership • Daily usage of Intelligence analyst tools, USSID’s, and databases including, but not limited to; ANALYST’S NOTEBOOK, PINWALE, CPE, MESSIAH, GALE-LITE, HOMEBASE, CADENCE, ArcGIS, ARCVIEW, SEDB, DISHFIRE, MAINWAY, TAPERLAY, RENOIR, OCTAVE, ANCHORY/MAUI, AIRGAP, AMHS, INTELINK, UIS, CONTRACTIVE, GEOFINDER, GOOGLE EARTH, and OILSTOCK, Microsoft Office 2007, Outlook, Word, Power Point, and Excel including experience with pivot tables

title: Strategic and Tactical Intelligence Consultant
description: Core Responsibilities: Create Strategic and Tactical intelligence plans in support of multi-disciplined service. Create strategic and tactical action plans in support of domestic and international missions. Build Intelligence training and policy standards, create strategic collection plans, assessments, build indicator platforms, refine active intelligence procedures, prepare active intelligence reports in support or mission operations, and create efficient strategic measures to enhance tactical applications. Liaise with domestic and international personnel in support of national defense, and the war on terror.

title: Proprietor
description: Our business is centered around a one of a kind product that houses and protects iPods, iPhones and iPads. The product is a fabric "uncase" constructed of reclaimed cashmere, cut from previously worn sweaters interfaced with a man-made optical cloth that cleans the glass surface of the iDevice. The products themselves, production, packaging and marketing are based on a holistic driven philosophy which focuses on thinking and acting more consciously and responsibly about our current lifestyle and our ongoing relationship to our enviornment. Our cashmere products are machine and hand-sewn by retired and disabled individuals. The cashmere is bought and collected from resale stores and estate sales. An option will be presented for customers to send in their own used cashmere sweater to be recycled for a custom item order. In addition to the product mentioned, for the iPad uncases, we are offering a break-apart form insert made of recycled material that can be used to build a stand and a cord wrap made from sustainable Basswood.

title: Technical Specialist
company: Pennsylvania Training and Technical Support Network
description: I provide technical support to educational consultants and a support staff of 48 working for the Pennsylvania Training and Technical Assistance Network (PaTTAN), a part of the Pennsylvania Department of Education, Bureau of Special Education funded by the federal IDEA grant. Our mission, as I see it, is to provide supports for Special Ed kids integrated into Regular Ed classrooms. Starting out providing network (AppleTalk) and technical support for Macintosh SE30s and Classic IIs, over the years I have supported both the Windows and Macintosh platforms and Lucent and Avaya phone systems. I have authored graphic design projects such as newsletters and strategic plans, and have used Macromedia Authorware and QuickTime to create multimedia products for our educational consultants. My primary areas of expertise today are software support, printing and telephony.

title: Publisher
description: AdventureTime started out in 1994 as a newsletter focusing on "extreme sports". I hammered it out on an Apple Macintosh Duo 280 and printed it on an HP LaserJet 4M printer. Increasing advertising revenue allowed for colorpress printing and, as the Internet evolved and printing costs increased, AT became web-only. Alas, the small Pittsburgh market, the fledging Internet of 1995 and increasing competition put the kibosh on continuing the publication as anything but a labor of love.

title: Landscape Designer
description: I have always liked plants and architecture and while studying at the University of Pittsburgh, I became enamored with landscape design while attending an Architectual Studies class. I started reading every book I could get my hands on about plants and landscape architects and their work. After college, I decided to give local landscape design a go and formed Animated Gardens. It was just me and my Nissan pick-up but I was able to convince local artist, Joan Brindel, to let me do a plan for her garden. This led to one referral after another. At the end of my reign, I had done full landscape design blueprints for over 15 clients. Other interests captured my attention but I continue to have a love for plants and their placement.

title: Proprietor
description: Spatz was an antique clothing store located on the mezzanine in the old Jenkins Arcade building (now 5th Ave Place) in downtown Pittsburgh. Purchased at estate sales, flea markets and old warehouses, previously worn and unworn mens and womens vintage clothing, shoes and accessories from the 30s 40s 50s and 60s were offered for sale in a boutique environment. Who can forget the painted parachute dressing room! One of the first vintage clothing shops in Pittsburgh! It was shuttered when Portfolio Magazine became too time-intensive.

title: President
description: My stint as "fashion designer"...at the time probably the only one in Pittsburgh (not to my advantage, actually)! A 20 yr old graduate of the Fashion Academy of Pittsburgh, I rented two industrial sewing machines, a second floor "showroom" overlooking the original Primanti Bros on 18th Street and a large dose of chutzpah. Under the label "GRANTED", I styled my "sportswear taffeta" (100% nylon) pieces and pinwale cut-on-the-bias corduroy outfits, ultrasuede shopping bags and shirred silk organza evening wear. They sold in Scoop, and Ruth Young and Adeles boutiques. American fashion at the time was "New York or Bust" and, and at the time, I didn't think I was cut out for the big city.

title: Senior Operations Manager/Project Coordinator [layoff]
description: Active TS/SCI, CI Clearance. Systems Engineering and Technical Assistance (SETA) Contractor. Provides support to Army Reprogramming Analysis Team (ARAT) Program Office, US Army Communications-Electronics Command (CECOM) Software Engineering Center. Directly aligned with and assists Division -level Operations. Programmatic support to Branch Chief. Liaison between Branches within the Division-ensures coordination, consolidation of input from three Branch Chiefs, and respective designees. Contributes data and insight for official reports, briefings and presentations, given at Directorate Level and higher. Collaboration and support to development and presentation of Program Management Reviews (PMRs). Familiar with Foreign Military Sales (FMS), Mission Data Sets (MDS), and software engineering activities. Administers Division suspense tracker, ensuring timely/accurate responses, contributing to higher suspense. Strategic and financial planning and analysis. Manages contract resource allocation/monitoring ($10M + projects), Work Breakdown Structures (WBS), Project Initiation/Project Tracking. Composing/disseminating meeting protocol; presentation development, meeting coordination. Construction and delivery of recurrent status reports. Initiates, executes and provides guidance (to Division staff, Branch Chiefs and Branch personnel) in Business Process Reengineering (BPR) and workflow management. Responsible for establishing and preserving sustainment processes. Serves as liaison between operational/technical staff and internal and external partners and key stakeholders. Participation in IPTs. Successfully established/executed automated processing and repository for once-manual Project Initiation Form and associated workflow. Extensive use of Sharepoint, Microsoft Office to include Excel, Word, PowerPoint, Project).

title: Performance/Business Intelligence Analyst
description: (Limited term, position canceled)--As part of The Performance Excellence and Assurance Management department, serves as a critical enabler of Center 10200's vision to deliver excellence in Supply Chain Management, providing quality/continuous improvement services, documented guidance, and performance assessments allow the organization to operate flexibly, effectively, and efficiently. Specific responsibilities include, but are not limited to: development, implementation/maintenance of ISO 9001 Quality Management System; interfacing with external government agencies and other stakeholders;overall performance measurement and evaluation; contractor performance evaluations; supplier quality; information technology strategy; continuous improvement services (e.g., lean six sigma, benchmarking). Responsible for developing, monitoring, and reporting on supply chain performance metrics, as well as identifying/evaluating opportunities for use of other resources to develop comprehensive metrics and data analytics. Works closely with supply chain senior management team and interfaces with large segments of the center's workforce. Leads ad hoc data requests, reports, and deliverables for senior management; leads Procurement and Logistics Customer Satisfaction surveys and reporting systems; leads Sandia's Contractor Review and Evaluation (SCORE) system, including Sandia's contractor improvement process. Works with Corporate Reporting and Planning Systems Department to develop reliable data and reports. Benchmarking other sites Procurement processes and performance. Provides systems-based solutions and support for Supplier Data Management efforts; ensures Sandia's performance assurance measures meet Sandia Corporation and U.S. Department of Energy requirement, using quality and risk management, assessment, root cause analysis, and performance measures. Synthesizes a variety of information into meaningful reports, using complex computer programs to mine data sources.

title: Business Operations Manager
description: Active TS/SCI Clearance. Serves as Business Operations Manager and consultant for strategic management issues, utilizing primarily tactical management. Accountable for planning and organizing government contract activities (practical knowledge of Task Order Contracts, Periods of Performance, Option years). Maintains daily operations. Formulates plans for use of materials and budget. Management of budget in coordination with the Regional Director. Reviews budgetary information and interprets financial data. Monthly and bi-monthly invoicing to funding sources. Assesses, plans, and develops recurrent budget for contract purposes. Monitors, develops, integrates and continues improvement in current processes and procedures associated with Information Management and strategy planning (improving as needed). Manages and increases effectiveness and efficiency of support services through coordination and communication between support and business functions. Improves the operational systems, processes and policies in support of organizations mission, specifically, management reporting, information flow, business process and organizational planning. Assists Regional Directors with program/project deliverables. Cooperation with bi-coastal regions in projecting long-term planning and initiatives geared toward operational growth. Oversees, designs, and controls nearly all aspects of business operations, ensuring efficiency and effectiveness in terms of meeting customer requirements. Extensive experience with Microsoft Office to include (not limited to): PowerPoint, Excel, Word. Comfortable working independently, as well as with a team. Excellent oral and written communication skills.

title: Program Analyst IV- Site Lead [Layoff]
description: Active TS/SCI,CI Clearance. Systems Engineering and Technical Assistance (SETA) Contractor in support of Sustainment for Software Engineering Branch. Regulates and manages program needs; assisting and liaising between directors, senior managers, program managers (for TGS, IPC, CHARCS, ENFIRE, MFLT, DCGS-A) to ensure quality program/project deliverables. Requirement analysis, integration, planning; RFI, RFP, and SOW familiarity; contract resource allocation/monitoring ($10M + projects). Estimation/Projection, Work Breakdown Structures (WBS); Program/Project Analysis and Assessment. Programmatic and Business Initiatives and contract oversight. Prepare Program Management Reviews (PMRs). Gather/translate business requirements; writing/reviewing whitepapers, memorandums; presentations. Constructs and delivers status reports for contract-specific analysis. Establishes, preserves, manages processes/workflows. Training personnel, maintaining project/team records and documentation. Process improvement efforts in core business practices: successful completion (as team) of two Class C, and one Class B Appraisals for Capability Maturity Model Integration (CMMI), part of a Standard CMMI Appraisal Method for Process Improvement (SCAMPI)); includes Quality Assurance audits. Familiarity with Federal Acquisition Regulations (FAR). Liaison between operational/technical staff and internal and external key stakeholders. As site lead, direct supervision of employees (recruitment, interview, work appraisal, retention, recognition. New-hire orientation (company introduction, benefits review, payroll, security); training, maintains employee records and documentation.

title: SIGINT Analyst [Impending Layoff]
description: Active TS/SCI clearance. Creates and supports computer-based scenarios in Joint, multi-echelon environment, used to train military intelligence personnel. Adjusts training scenarios to analyze students' reactions to information provided from various disciplines. Builds complete solutions to support overall exercise objectives, while reflecting Tactics, Techniques, and Procedures observed in current military operations and from Army Training Transformation program's Lessons Learned initiative. Generates predefined SIGINT message traffic, background reports and finished intelligence products to portray aspects of Command, Control, Communications, Computers, Intelligence, Surveillance and Reconnaissance (C4ISR) environment. Provides research and data mining of current Contemporary Operational Environment including both enemy operations and friendly capabilities. Authors activity timelines, maps and associated overlays. Establishes and maintains student user accounts on multiple computer systems. Functions as white cell during exercise operations delivering pre-scripted traffic and responding to requests for information. Use of Psi/MerchChat, ArcGIS, Bellview, NIPR, SIPR, JWICS, NTNG (exercise specific), DSE (exercise specific).

title: Senior Consultant/Associate (LandWarNet Action Officer)
description: Active TS/SCI clearance. Action Officer. Ensures LandWarNet (LWN) programs initiatives are in compliance with vision and timelines established by Executive echelons. Coordinates, attends Council of Colonels and General Officers Steering Committee meetings as LandWarNet/Intelligence Center Representative/liaison. Develops, edits, reviews papers characterizing progress toward integrated future capabilities. Research and develop intelligence-related programs; provides guidance, conducts analysis on, provides recommendations for improvement in Doctrine, Organization, Training, Materiel, Leadership and Education, Personnel and Facilities (DOTMLPF). Utilizes Joint Capabilities Integration and Development System (JCIDS) process and Capability Based Assessments (CBA) process. As Executive Liaison, coordinates with Army G-2, Office of the Deputy Chief of Staff for Intelligence (ODCSINT); Army G-3, Office of the Deputy Chief of Staff for Operations and Plans (ODCSOPS); G-6, Office of the Deputy Chief of Information Officer/G6 (CIO/G6); and Army G-8, Office of the Deputy Chief of Staff. Performs executive-level management, oversight and decision-making. Excellent management skills and business acumen. Business development- strategic analysis/marketing. Identifying new business, manage relationships between company and Government.

title: Force Development Test and Evaluation Analyst [Impending Layoff]
description: Active TS/SCI clearance. Program and force development analyst. Plans, coordinates, analyzes and manages changes to Army and Joint warfighting capabilities documents, specifically the Army Intelligence Comprehensive Guide to Modularity (AICGM). Utilization of intelligence processes and advanced research techniques to define joint Intelligence, Surveillance and Reconnaissance (ISR) system and capabilities for ISR Information Paper. Thorough knowledge, skills, and abilities (KSAs) in areas related to principles and concepts of the National Intelligence Community (with emphasis on Air Force and Army), Intelligence products, data collection and analysis, evaluation, interpretation, Army Universal Task List (AUTL) and Unit Task List (UTL), and dissemination of sensitive information. Technical writer/editor. Develops analytical documents and de-conflicts information about force structure coordination and integration. Contributes to independent studies related to Force Management and Force Structure. Effectively executes feasibility/affordability/suitability reviews and reports; integrates information into aspects of force modernization, force structure, mission area/capability, system compatibility, and combat balance to optimize accomplishment of the Army mission.

title: Doctrine and Course Development/Analyst
description: Doctrine Developer/Editor: Active TS/SCI clearance. Works for Deputy Director of Doctrine at the US Army Intelligence Center and Fort Huachuca, Futures Directorate, and Concepts Division. Authors/edits unclassified Signals Intelligence (SIGINT) Field Manual. Primary POC for creation, revision, dissemination of SIGINT manual in accordance with DOD, Department of the Army (DA), and United States Army TRADOC and Doctrinal Literature Program. Collaborates with representatives from National Security Agency (NSA), United States Army Intelligence and Security Command (INSCOM), United States Special Operations Command (SOCOM), and U.S. Army Special Forces Command (USASFC) to name a few. Created and maintains continuity book to map timelines, targets, milestones and completions of SIGINT field manual (FM). Subject matter expert concerning [military] technical document construction editing, grammatical consistency, clarity, publication preparation. Instructor/Course Developer:Large-group Instructor, Tactical Electronic Warfare Operations (EWO) Course, Ft. Huachuca. Conducts instruction to DOD civilians/joint service military members, ranging from E-4 through E-9, O-1 through O-5. Develops, organizes, reviews, conducts training. Conducts/directs field training in a closed-course environment. Develops criteria for evaluation. Extensive knowledge of Intelligence, Electronic Warfare and Sensors (IEWS); Army's Military Decision-Making Process (MDMP). Intelligence Surveillance and Reconnaissance (ISR) systems. Research and analysis. Teaches basics of: Prophet, UAV/UAS (Shadow/Hunter/(MQ-1, MQ-9) Reaper/Global Hawk), MEWSS/MAGTF, RC 135 RIVET JOINT, EA-6B, DCGS-A. Administrative operations related to course evaluations/documentation. Prepares policies and procedures for course and/or field application. Exhibits proficiency in human relations and adult instruction. ASAT (Automated Systems Approach to Training) familiarity. Attended Instructor Training Course (ITC/BITC).
